# Introduction to Basic Statistics in R

R, originally developed as a statistical programming language, is a perfect tool for performing basic statistics. Many built-in functions and community developed packages make for a seamless statistical analysis experience. This lesson will cover some statistical tests that you come across when working with environmental data.

```card:info
Throughout this lesson, we will use an ozone data set called `chicago_air` to demonstrate these concepts.
```

First, we need to load this ozone data and assign the ozone column to its own variable for quick access.

```r
library(region5air)
data(chicago_air)
ozone <- chicago_air$ozone
```

## Descriptive and Exploratory Statistics

R offers a number of built-in functions for descriptive statistics. The functions we will be exploring all have a parameter `na.rm` that instructs the function to exclude any `NA` values from the calculation.

Let's explore the range and the spread of our dataset:

```r
min(ozone, na.rm=T)
max(ozone, na.rm=T)
range(ozone, na.rm=T)
summary(ozone)
```

To visualize the data distribution, `hist()` and `boxplot()` come in handy.

```r
hist(ozone)
boxplot(ozone)
```

